A woman with a MILK truck is running from tyranical patriarch, who chases her, from a valley of the dead. Then she decides with the help of a road Warrior, a death embodiment, to face the tyrant and regain her home. She is dying and Death gives her his blood and then leaves to the road.
Such movies are rarity. But I see what you mean. Too simple a story. But not without a story.
author: Mad Hat (tah-dam)

text:
¬†@Mad Hat (tah-dam)¬† I know it has a story technically. That was a bit of an exaggeration. It's still pretty silly though. 

The only reason why they drove back in the first place, is because they know there are no further resources out there for them. All the food and water is back home where they came from. So why didn't they think about that earlier before attempting the initial escape? The lack of character development (especially Max himself) was another thing that bothered me.

Don't get me wrong it's definitely an entertaining movie and all with great visuals and master editing, but I still wouldn't compare it to a movie as well written, well acted, well directed, and well scored as TDK. 

Directing a Batman movie as a crime thriller was just genius filmmaking on Christopher Nolan's behalf. But with all that being said, I still respect your opinion.

author: Tarang Nair

text:
¬†@Tarz√°n TABI¬† My personal list as of yet is:

1. The Social Network 
2. There Will Be Blood
3. Spirited Away
4. Mulholland Drive
5. Inglourious Basterds
6. Return of The King
7. The Departed
8. Fellowship of The Ring
9. The Dark Knight
10. City of God

As for some explanation, I do agree with the video that The Social Network is probably the best of the century. Not only is it the most culturally relevant, but it's flawlessly written, flawlessly directed, extremely well acted, has a phenomenal musical score, expertly edited, etc. 

I feel like it's a movie that gets spat on because it just seems like a movie about facebook when it's really so much more than that. 

As for There Will Be Blood, there isn't much to say about this movie. It's a true American masterpiece about religion, human nature, and capitalism. Daniel Day-Lewis gifts us with one of the greatest cinematic performances of all time, easily the best of the century. It's deliberately and meticulously paced, and expertly directed. An excellent musical score, well developed characters, stacked cast, etc. 

Spirited Away is just the greatest animated movie hands down. It's a gorgeous movie and complex and well written characters and a wacky yet intriguing world to get sucked into. Miyazaki's best film to date. 

Mulholland Drive is a crazy mindfuck of a film, in a good way. Expertly directed, well acted, and well scripted, this movie works on every level. Hard to understand at first, it's a cinematic experience that sticks long after the film is finished. 

Return of The King is just amazing. I don't know what else to say. It's perfect. The perfect conclusion to possibly the greatest trilogy ever made. 

The Departed is a fantastic movie. Very well paced and directed, expertly edited, extremely well acted, memorable and well implemented music, a tense and tightly written script, etc. 

I will likely move Fellowship down a few spots, but it's a phenomenal  movie nonetheless

The Dark Knight...ooh. The Dark Knight is a masterpiece. I think originally, it was number 1 on the list, but over time I've found flaws in it that have made each viewing experience less enjoyable. But it is a fantastic movie nonetheless. 

City of God is one of the most well edited and shot films I've ever seen. It's basically Goodfellas on crack for just how authentic and crazy it is. While it isn't necessarily better than Goodfellas, it's a damn near perfect movie
